===subject:The Columbian Exchange
===from:Jasmine Heard
===date:Fri May 30  0:20:48 2003
===message:I totally agree with Jesse Caudill in that the Native Americans lost most from the Columbian Exchange and the gift to them was diseases. I also agree that the Americans gained the most from the Columbian Exchange. Although the Americans experienced some decline in population due to the spread of diseases, the long-term result was an increase in population from the spread of the crops and animals delivered from the Europeans. 
The most important gift from the Americas was the generosity to share their crops with other countries. The crops that took route in Africa, Asia and Europe included maize, potatoes, tomatoes, and peanuts (just to name a few). The results of the Americas' generosity were an increase in calories in Eurasian diet, and added protein, vitamins and zesty flavors to foods.

=========yorg=========
